Files:
- plugins/linear/src/tools/batch-update-issues.ts (fix GraphQL injection)

Context:
The `batch_update_issues` tool builds a GraphQL mutation with aliased fields for each issue ID. Currently, the issue IDs are interpolated directly into the query string using template literals with double quotes:

```
const aliases = params.issue_ids.map(
  (id, i) =>
    `issue${i}: issueUpdate(id: "${id}", input: $input) {
    success
    issue { ${ISSUE_FIELDS} }
  }`,
);
```

A crafted issue ID containing a double-quote character (`"`) could break out of the GraphQL string literal and inject arbitrary GraphQL operations.

Changes:
The fix requires passing each issue ID as a separate GraphQL variable. Change the approach to:
1. Build a variables object with `$id0: ID!, $id1: ID!, ...` for each issue
2. Reference these variables in the mutation aliases: `issueUpdate(id: $id0, input: $input)`
3. Pass the actual ID values in the variables dict alongside `input`

Example approach:
```typescript
const varDefs = params.issue_ids.map((_, i) => `$id${i}: String!`).join(', ');
const aliases = params.issue_ids.map(
  (_, i) =>
    `issue${i}: issueUpdate(id: $id${i}, input: $input) {
    success
    issue { ${ISSUE_FIELDS} }
  }`,
);
const query = `mutation BatchUpdateIssues($input: IssueUpdateInput!, ${varDefs}) {
  ${aliases.join('\n')}
}`;
const vars: Record<string, unknown> = { input };
params.issue_ids.forEach((id, i) => { vars[`id${i}`] = id; });
const data = await graphql<...>(query, vars);
```

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the aliased mutation pattern (issue0, issue1, ...) — the result parsing depends on these alias names
- Do NOT change the ISSUE_FIELDS constant
- The $input variable must remain as-is
